key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advancements in game theory and statistics from the last century - particula
rly the theory of decision under risk - can explain some of the seeming
 irrationality of consumer behaviour that Veblen had observed in the late
 19th century (see von Neumann-Morgenstern
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VonNeumannMorgenstern1944"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Dhami 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 While the effect that social conditions have on human behaviour still remains
 an area of research 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "StraussEcoGeo2008"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we argue that it is possible within the remit of the theory to view status
 consumption - i.e.
 the disproportionate spending on goods that only have a status (or visible)
 appeal - as an instance of the consumer's risk-seeking behaviour.
 The two threads in the literature on status consumption which we have surveyed
 - first related to the behavioural approaches to life-cycle model and second
 related to the significance of social characteristics in visible consumption
 - can both be linked with this formulation of status.
 In linking the two threads, we rely on the intertemporal substitution problem
 - where a rational utility-optimising consumer balances between the non-durable
 and durable consumption based on her planned savings over her life-time
 (a problem often treated equivalent to the classical utility maximising
 consumption problem).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In first set of literature, a notable study is due to Shefrin-Thaler 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShefrinThaler1988"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who seek a descriptive model for mental accounting (factors such as willpower)
 to explain observed trends in consumption.
 Unlike in the classical variants of the theory of consumer choice - where
 the consumer is subservient to her optimised plan for life-time savings
 and consumption - the representative consumer in a behavioural model is
 subject to overeating, overspending, accumulating items she doesn't need
 or acquiring habits she cannot afford (see Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a classical treatment of habit formation and consumer myopia).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second set of literature observes the demand on visible items across
 several economies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia,CharlesHurstRace,KausSA,OmoriSmithVisRace,FrieheGermany,ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A key assumption made by such studies is that conspicuous consumption brings
 no utility in the regular sense (see Ireland 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Hopkins-Kornienko 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The argument - often attributed to Veblen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - allows one to consider the utility for visible consumption separable
 (additively) from the utility for non-visible consumption (we refer to
 this assumption as the futility assumption henceworth).
 The studies on visible consumption consistently find that segregated social
 groups (e.g.
 the black population in South Africa
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, religious groups in India
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and regions of erstwhile East Germany
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) spend differently on visible items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finding similar conclusions as this second set of literature, the studies
 in marketing
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JacksonConsIdent1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and political economy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have also explored the themes of identity, ownership and consumption in
 the respective contexts.
 The role that industrial goods and income rises play in the addressing
 of status needs by the consumers (see Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 ) has in fact been of interest to many sociological studies in the post-war
 era.
 In India of the 1950s, for example, Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 noted an instance of Veblen's pecuniary emulation
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 (referred to as 
\shape italic
Sanskritization
\shape default
) as the erstwhile lower classes emulated the habits of higher social classes
 with their newly acquired economic freedoms.
 Elsewhere too, rapid industrialisation has been noted to have created a
 disproportionate change in lifestyles with a crowding effect towards urbanisati
on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The empirical analyses based on such studies - however - have been of a
 limited scope due to the unobserved nature of some of the factors identified
 in the studies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach we use to incorporate the role of personal characteristics
 in the intertemporal setting derives much from Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 - who motivate a case for a ranking order of status (so that the consumer
 always attempts to move herself up in the status order).
 In our adaptation of the intertemporal substitution problem, we view snob
 and bandwagon behaviours as the fundamental mechanisms for any status utility
 availed by the consumer
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The mutually opposing mechanisms that Veblen defined were pecuniary emulation
 and invidious comparison - indicating the trends in consumption where the
 not-so rich may emulate the rich (pecuniary emulation) or show to the poor
 that they belong to a club that poor don't (invidious comparison).
 We have found Corneo's terminology more tractable for empirical analyses
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "true"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In the presence of uncertainty related to wealth, the consumer's place
 in the status order can be viewed as the long-term security of the consumer
 from extreme fluctuations in her (higher) wealth.
 This is the sense in which status is usually interpreted in the studies
 in health and sociological sciences - which often track status as a vector
 of income, education and occupation (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples).
 However, a demand equation for status goods that considers status as a
 mere demographic vector ignores the dynamic nature of status and the demand
 for bandwagon items - which also influence the consumer's perception of
 status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status, being a social psychological concern, is observed only at the level
 of a social unit (individual or a reference group).
 So while a researcher observing a population of consumers may interpret
 status as the risk-adjusted net worth of the individual - i.e.
 the total net-worth combined with the risk associated with the transition
 to the highest band of net-worth in the long-term - the consumer necessarily
 has a subjective view of her status.
 This subjective view of status is influenced by local factors that may
 be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

averaged out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at higher levels - what status means at the consumer's level may in fact
 even disagree with what status means at a higher societal-level.
 This is because the consumer's view of status would respond to the socio-politi
cal conditions that she perceives from within a particular social unit (family,
 community, ethnicity or region) than to the observed variables that are
 standardised over a larger area.
 The sense of status consumption is therefore necessarily localised at the
 consumer's social reference level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is only from a rather ontological perspective, that a high-status individual
 is someone who, in the long-term, has either or both of high income and
 a high (inter-generational) probability to move towards the high income
 group (stability).
 Let's call this the 
\shape italic
observed 
\shape default
probability of wealth transition (i.e.
 a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{ij}\}$
\end_inset

 representing the transition from wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

) - which the researcher observes.
 A low-status individual - similarly - is someone who has either or both
 of low net worth and a low 
\shape italic
observed 
\shape default
probability of transition to high net worth.
 Concerned with the long-term effect of such factors to the asset ownership
 and stability of income, while a researcher could assume that all consumers
 observe the same probability of transition to higher state of income, the
 consumer at local levels would in fact be motivated by the particular short-ter
m concerns with respect to the social unit that shape her view of status
 of others and her own self-image.
 Thus the uncertainty of wealth transition is observed at multiple levels
 in this subjective formulation of probability.
 The probability of material wealth transition that a consumer associates
 with the future is fundamentally subjective - although determined largely
 by factors related to social or regional identity.
 For the purposes of this discussion, we consider this latter sense as the
 consumer's 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 probability of wealth transition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This subjective uncertainty is a mere restatement of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peer-effects
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that influence the consumer's decision.
 The consumer's assumed
\shape italic
 subjective 
\shape default
probability is driven by an indeterminate number of factors such as her
 occupation, education, social or familial background, personality types
 etc.
 and is subject to change over the her lifetime.
 Since consumption is usually myopic, such a view would influence consumption
 at all times.
 Thus while the notion of status influence the risk-seeking behaviour of
 the consumer at local levels, the growth in the income and wealth of the
 consumer are constrained with long-term economic conditions (represented
 with the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability).
 One may thus use the long-term ownership of assets observed over time as
 the sense of consumer's wealth which reconciles the respective subjective
 probability functions of all the consumers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a reconciliation is possible only because in the long-term there is
 no difference between the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 and 
\shape italic
subjective
\shape default
 probabilities.
 While the non-durable consumption of the consumers would be associated
 with their view in the short-term, in the long-term what matters is whether
 they have achieved a higher state of wealth (and thus status) or not.
 To illustrate this with an example, consider three consumers with different
 occupations in a small economy - an academic, a sportsperson and an investor
 - who all share the share the same reference point (by assumption) for
 wealth.
 They would all estimate the probability of doubling their wealth in the
 lifetime so that they may retire on the successful achievement of their
 goal.
 Given the nature of the profession, it is likely that the sportsperson
 overestimates the probability of her success until the middle of her career
 - after which the probability she associates to the success of doubling
 her wealth (if she hasn't already) would decline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus a risk-seeking behaviour would be associated with a sportsperson much
 the way a risk-averse behaviour is associated with the academic who may
 be well aware of the limited probability of a windfall in the short-term.
 On the other hand, an investor may obtain a definite gain over a fixed
 term and have a risk-profile that lies somewhere in between that of the
 sportsperson and the academic.
 While the long-term decisions of the sportsperson may still be determined
 by the knowledge of expected income, a sportsperson would be characterised
 by a belief in an unlikely probability of success in the near-term in a
 way that is different from how an academic or an investor would foresee
 her future possible wealth transition.
 If we can assume that the three consumers have the same basic needs, it
 is unlikely that the consumption of the three individuals would be independent
 of how they view the transition probability of their monetary wealth in
 the near term.
 Still in the long-term it is only their success in monetary terms that
 would track their status.
 To state whether a risk-seeking consumer spends more or less on non-durable
 consumption we attempt to understand the consumer's goal in the intertemporal
 setting (where status consumption may appear to be less beneficial than
 saving for assets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the above outline of a model, we can separate the consumer's choice
 that would impart varied degrees of certainty - the most certain choice
 being of a cash asset and the most uncertain choices being an unnecessary
 piece of jewelry.
 We represent the group of durable goods indicating a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

certain
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth acquisition as a wealth account 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 (at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 ) - which she utilises regardless of her risk-appetite.
 Thus a risk-seeking individual may get more utility from the non-durable
 consumption than the risk-averse individual (see Lowenstein-Prelec 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LowensteinPrelec1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Brenner et al and Shu et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BrennerVLA2007,ShuPeckOwnership2011"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for the relation between loss-aversion and possessions).
 If the long-term assets can be considered as part of the wealth that can
 be passed on to generations, the short-term concerns of the consumer (which
 are influenced by the acquired wealth) are sensitive to the degree of risk-aver
sion
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The fulfilment of basic consumer needs itself carries no influence on status.
 Thus if we were to compare the consumption of a risk-seeking consumers
 with that of a risk-averse consumer, the consumption on needs would not
 have any role to play in the utility towards status relative to one another.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we associate non-durable consumption with the subjective probability,
 the status-related consumption (seen as high non-durable consumption) can
 be viewed as the consumer's risk-seeking behaviour in terms of the the
 
\shape italic
subjective 
\shape default
and 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probabilities.
 Those who are hoping to enhance their social network or get ahead of others
 through signaling are likely to believe in a higher likelihood of their
 promotion to a higher status.
 A higher probability for the state promotion perceived by a risk-seeking
 consumer would thus result in a higher (subjective) weight for the same
 observed probability.
 Similarly, the perceived (weighted) probability of loss of one's status
 would be higher (e.g.
 that of the threat of immigration to one's personal wealth) than the 
\shape italic
observed
\shape default
 probability in the long-term for a risk-averse consumer
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The arguments for subjective probability that we use to develop our status
 consumption model have been around at least since Keynes.
 A more formal treatment of subjective probability is offered by de Finetti
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "vonPlato2012"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Savage
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Savage1972"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 .
 The term personal probability (instead of perceived probability) is used
 by Savage to imply a probability associated with a consequence.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A probability weighting function can be chosen to represent the different
 weighting of observed probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At this point, it is worthwhile to speak of the economic processes that
 are implied by an interplay of the two levels of uncertainties that we
 use to relate risk-aversion with consumption.
 One way to view the two uncertainties is as a delay or barriers in the
 flow of information related to risks in the consumer markets.
 When it comes to risks to the future wealth, the firms and institutions
 are often better equipped and more responsive than the individuals or small
 communities.
 The differences in subjective uncertainties and observed uncertainties
 matter only because of the differences in how information is consumed at
 different levels of societal organisation (e.g.
 at the level of consumption and at the level where incomes are distributed).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a presence of barriers to information also indicates a limit to the
 free-market assumption of an autonomous consumer fully capable of addressing
 her true needs (see a discussion in Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Doyal-Gough
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 There is little doubt that the differences in purchasing power between
 sections of a society and their desire for mobility can drive the consumption
 and the economy (see Smith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SmithMoralSentiments"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 But the implicit assumption in the free market view of an exchange between
 the rich and poor sections driving economic progress is that the consumer
 has full information of the risks and incentives related to her wealth
 (i.e.
 the economy functions in a way that these risks are known to the consumer).
 If barriers to the flow of information the strength of institutions both
 undergo severe changes, this exchange may become less or more feasible
 (see Hirsch
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Galbraith 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GalbraithEssential,GalbraithAffluent"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Indeed such effects are more likely to be observed in the economies undergoing
 structural changes such as rapid industrialisation, higher advertising
 effects or increased centralisation of markets.
 So long as one may admit that the information about socio-economic changes
 is consumed at different speeds and extent amongst the consumers than firms
 then it must follow that the two consider the information of risks differently.
 The consumption in the short-term would thus always be influenced by asymmetrie
s in the observation of risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For these different levels of uncertainty to make any empirical sense however
 the subjective views of the consumer must be rationalised with the observed
 economic variables in the long run.
 The resources in an economy evolve as they are influenced by the actions
 taken on beliefs rather than beliefs themselves.
 In the long-run, the consumer beliefs reflect the changes in long-term
 assets by letting the risk-averse behaviours balance the risk-seeking behaviour
s participate in the same economy.
 Therefore we reconcile the consumers' subjective probability functions
 with an observed trajectory of wealth over a sufficiently long-period (
 this is implied with the properties of a probability weighting function
 ).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A comparison with the permanent income hypothesis (PIH) can explain how
 this rationalisation of subjective probabilities could work in an intertemporal
 setting.
 The fundamental claim of the PIH is that income has a transitory and a
 permanent component where the consumption is directly proportional to the
 permanent component
\begin_inset Foot
status open

