\begin_layout Standard
Equivalent to the PIH's zero-correlation assumption is the reconciliation
 of the subjective probabilities with the observed probability in a stochastic
 process representing the evolution of wealth over time.
 We treat the items or characteristics that are passed on to the next generation
 as a part of consumer wealth while the items that cannot be passed on are
 considered short-term.
 In other words, the observed probability is contributed to by only the
 assets transferred between generations in the long-run - there is little
 more than the net asset worth of the individual and the personal characteristic
s (such as social class) that are passed over as inheritance to the progeny.
 On the other hand, the subjective probability of success through social
 interactions and the high quality consumption associated with it need not
 matter in the long-term - since the path to net asset worth may completely
