\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our view of status consumption as simply the excess non-durable consumption
 could appear incongruous with how conspicuous consumption is usually presented
 in the public discourse i.e.
 as a phenomenon that only-serves-the-rich.
 Generally speaking, we view a conspicuous item as one that can be used
 both to distance oneself from the others and to emulate the behaviour of
 those above oneself, but there is a tendency to focus more on its wastefulness
 amongst the rich than its utility to the middle classes.
 If one could admit a definition of status consumption as a means to distinguish
 oneself from one's own reference group and agree that everyone does belong
 to a particular reference group, then it follows that everyone can benefit
 from status consumption (i.e.
 a probabilistic improvement of the consumer's perceived status can be achieved
 with status consumption).
 Further, if the long-term consumption is defined as assets that stay the
 same over many generations (so that all else is considered non-durable)
 then a focus on non-durable consumption may sufficiently capture the sense
 of conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the presence of significant wealth differences, another reason to object
 to the view of status consumption as a consumption exclusive to the rich
 is that the utility to the rich from status consumption might be quite
 little given that the rich consumer already has enough to distance herself
 from others.
 Except for indicating a membership to the club of its owners, the marginal
 utility a conspicuous item offers to the rich consumer who may have just
 fallen short of means to signal her wealth is much less than what it may
 offer to the believers of social mobility who are trapped in an environment
 of lower-asset ownership.
 The argument that considers conspicuous consumption as only serving the
 rich may rule out conspicuous consumption by the poorest who don't have
 anyone else to leave behind (much the way the richest don't need to leave
 anyone behind).
 Instead, one could argue that even the poorest may want to indicate that
 they are not the poorest - much the way richest may want it to be known
 to the others that they are indeed the richest
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Any model of signalling or visible consumption
