LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals,HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 can be used to make this argument.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Made ubiquitous through expanding markets and increased awareness of items
 through advertisement, therefore, signaling through non-durable consumption
 may in fact be needed by both the rich and the poor.
 Indeed everyone else in the middle (i.e.
 those who are neither the richest nor the poorest) must also try to avoid
 getting poorer and try to become the richest at all times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, our approach for status consumption - similar to those used
 in the studies on visible consumption - is one that views a consumer's
 net utility from status consumption as a combination of private utility
 (subjective) and public utility (observed through rise in wealth).
 Where it differs fundamentally is in its treatment of uncertainty - establishin
g a relationship between the extreme wealth differences and the upside risk
 with consumption.
 Formulating status consumption as uncertainty associated with the future
 states of wealth and the utility from status consumption as a probabilistic
 private utility, we use prospect theory (PT) to understand a competition
 for status.
 A key difference from the approach taken in much of the literature on visible
 consumption is therefore that the status utility from such consumption
 is not futile in a material sense.
 Indeed a luxury watch may be futile for private use by itself (when compared
 to its cheaper alternatives that offer the same functionality i.e.
 that of telling the current time) but if an aspiring businessman uses his
 knowledge of luxury watches to find new clients for her business, then
 the futile consumption may probabilistically translate into a material
 advantage.
 The promise of social mobility is indeed the core appeal of status consumption.
 Items like luxury watches are in fact important only because the rich flock
 around them 
\begin_inset Foot
