\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Stochastic"

\end_inset

Stochastic Case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have argued before - the assumption of wealth depreciating or rising
 at a constant rate is too limiting for the purpose of modeling the effect
 on uncertainty on consumer choice.
 To represent a scenario closer to the real-world, we consider an uncertainty
 both in the consumer's perception of her future wealth and that in the
 path followed by wealth.
 The perception of the consumer is represented with a probability weighting
 function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016,KarmakarSWU1978"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A wealthy individual in the model does not just silently earn interest
 on income - but has to compete with others who are acquiring new wealth
 by investing into newer areas.
 Competing with others and guarding one's wealth, the consumer has no choice
 but to bet on uncertain pursuits in order for her to grow her wealth
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We make no attempts to model the processes of creative destruction that
 create new goods and services affecting wealth of some vs that of others.
 It is assumed that those with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wealth have full information of the new wealth opportunities (full information
 market) and therefore new wealth is replaced interchangeably with old wealth
 in the model through risky investments.
 The only competition that thus exists in this model economy is between
 the risk-seeking individuals and risk-averse individuals.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the stochastic formulation, the consumer's intertemporal choice is viewed
 as a simple lottery scheme.
 As the consumer's investments (i.e.
 consumption which is indistinguishable from needs) are hoped to increase
 the asset in some way, the expectation of growth in one's assets is embedded
 in the expenditure one makes.
 Anything that is not expended contributes to the saving towards wealth
 for the consumer.
 Over generations the wealth can either decline significantly or grow in
 value due to the strategy adopted by the consumer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since staying in an elite non-durable consumption club offers only a probabilist
ic benefit, we represent the consumer's choice as one amognst many lotteries.
 The examples for such an expenditure would be a club membership or expertise
 in conspicuous items which might eventually get the consumer in the rich
 club over generations albeit with a low probability.
 The various lotteries available to the consumer could range from a secure
 cash savings to a balanced strategy of spending towards education in the
 hope for income rise over years or a bet on an expensive club membership
 in a hope for relevant social connections.
 Note the consumer's own risk-profile always influences the selection of
 a particular lottery.
 In other words, the same observed probability may be considered too risky
 or not risky enough for consumers with different degrees of risk-aversion
 (a feature that is modeled with the probability weighting function
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016,KarmakarSWU1978"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Probability-Weighting-Function-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using prospect theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KahnemanTversykPT1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 we elaborate a utility function that evaluates the various lotteries for
 a consumer.
 Any given lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is seen as a sequence of payoffs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $u(L)=\sum_{i}w(p_{i})\upsilon(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)$
\end_inset

 is the probability weighting function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(x)$
\end_inset

 is the payoff-utility function for the consumer).
 If we assign probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\{p_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 to the various options 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 distributed with a known distribution function to the consumer, we can
 assess the relative importance of the options to the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not having assumed a depreciation or an interest-based growth with the wealth
 account allows us to attribute the growth or depreciation in the wealth
 account to the consumer's perceived uncertainty in an environment of risky
 future growth for wealth.
 To accentuate the uncertainty in the growth of wealth, consider a gold
 rush economy where more digging increases the chances of getting a higher
 wealth.
 This is comparable to finding new wealth in an economy - where luck favours
 the prepared.
 Except through consumption, there is no inherent depreciation assumed for
 the wealth.
 This means that an immense wealth would deplete only with a high rate of
 consumption.
 It also means that if a consumer makes no new investments (search for gold)
 the competing consumers might find more wealth leading to her relative
 poverty in the economy.
 Both consumption and investment - which are indistinguishable empirically
 - are represented as one variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Recall that consumers are dynasties - and the life-cycle effects are ignored.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A general random process is assumed which scales up the success probability
 with the investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 so that an income 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is rewarded to the consumer in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a random variable observed in the economy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a general function with diminishing returns (digging more mines cannot
 infinitely increase one's wealth at a non-decreasing rate).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net effect of investments 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 on wealth is therefore risky in the stochastic model.
 We now explain a discrete model in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Discrete-Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 before providing an outline of how an extension could be made into a continuous
 model in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Continuous-Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 It is worth noting that in contrast with the non-stochastic approach, the
 consumer utility under risk is fundamentally different from the utility
 derived without risk (see Shoemaker
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ShoemakerEU1982"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a detailed discussion).
 The PT utility dictates that the behaviour of a risk-seeking consumer would
 be different in the stochastic model from that of a risk-averse consumer.
 More particularly, a consumer is allowed to have an irrational expectation
 of closing the wealth gap in the stochastic model whereas the non-stochastic
 utility model implied that a consumer with lower wealth could always get
 the same overall utility as a consumer with higher wealth if their consumption
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 are dissimilar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection

\series bold
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Discrete-Model"

\end_inset

Discrete Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a discrete model we use a Bernoulli trial which provides an uncertain
 payoff based on the investment 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing with the two consumer model, we assume that both the consumers
 observe the same process given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
A_{t+1}-A_{t} & =-\delta\psi+\sigma(\psi)X_{t}\label{eq:Bernoulli_dynamics}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is the rate at which the consumption depletes the wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)$
\end_inset

 is a non-decreasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 but also represents diminishing returns from 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus one cannot put infinite sized bets on 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 which is a Bernoulli random variable with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Summing over, one can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
A_{T} & =A_{0}-\delta\psi T+\sigma(\psi)\sum_{t=1}^{T}X_{t}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 varied over time periods 
\begin_inset Formula $1...T$
\end_inset

, we could use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=\sum_{i=1}^{t}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a binomial variable of size 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to write:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
A_{T} & =A_{0}-\delta\psi_{t}T+\sigma(\psi)B_{T}\label{eq:bernoulli_asset}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be simplified just the way in the non-stochastic case if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is held to be the same throughout all periods so that only the optimal
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to maximise utility in the dynamics of Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Bernoulli_dynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is considered.
 Given the limited supported for expected-value maximisation in behavioural
 experiments, we reject the approaches where the value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t+1}$
\end_inset

 is optimised by the consumer in favour of those where the consumer optimises
 a utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{t+1})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest of such cases are those where 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{t+1})$
\end_inset

 is enhanced with some risk-aversion parameters (see Sharpe 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SharpeEU2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 It follows with the function 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{t+1})$
\end_inset

 that a a risk neutral consumer making a one-time decision on 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 based on a time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 would choose a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{CE}$
\end_inset

 with uncertainty imposed by 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t\in[1,T]}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u(A_{T}))=u(A_{T})$
\end_inset

 is maximised.
 A risk-seeking consumer would choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{CE}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u(A_{CE}))=u(A_{CE})$
\end_inset

.
 The consumer choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $E($
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{T}))>E(u(A_{CE}))$
\end_inset

 is considered risk-seeking and the consumer selecting 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u(A_{T}))<E(u(A_{CE}))$
\end_inset

 would be considered risk-averse.
 If we use a CRRA utilty to illustrate this further, then 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A)=\frac{A^{1-\gamma}-1}{1-\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u(A_{T}))$
\end_inset

 is a non-decreasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{T}$
\end_inset

 leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{T})$
\end_inset

 being maximised when 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A_{T})$
\end_inset

 is maximised with 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:(\frac{d\sigma}{d\psi}=\frac{1}{p(1-p)})$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\sigma}{d\psi}>0$
\end_inset

).
 The measure of risk-aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 in the CRRA function is essentially a measure of the curvature of a value
 function.
 If every consumer optimises 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A_{T})$
\end_inset

 then consumer has no reason to deviate from the maximum 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A_{T})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is unlikely to represent a real-world scenario.
 Firstly, the consumer derives utility also from consumption (which we have
 already noted).
 Secondly, there is little evidence in support of the consumer preference
 following a CRRA or CARA type utility (see Dhami
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SanjitDhamiBehavioural2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Notice that there is something peculiar about the simple dynamics of Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Bernoulli_dynamics"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 - it is that wealth under a perceived uncertainty is controlled only through
 consumption (or investments 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

).
 This represents a particular situation of uncertainty in growth of wealth
 such that i) wealth declines only through consumption (risk) and ii) the
 consumption (risk taken) is fully under control of the consumer.
 We can thus view the differences caused by the degrees of risk-aversion
 if we assume a diminishing returns for a risky gain 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using PT allows us to incorporate the desired feature where not every consumer
 has same response to the same 
\shape italic
observed 
\shape default
probability of growth in wealth.
 To model the attitude towards risk, we consider a weighting of probability
 to differentiate the risk-seeking behaviour from the risk-averse behaviour.
 Also since we let the consumption and investments 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 track the perceived uncertainty in the stochastic dynamics, we no longer
 need to worry about the combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 - as they are equivalent to the combination of risk and value in PT.
 Note that a consumer who chooses no risk would set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=0$
\end_inset

 in the model specified by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:bernoulli_asset"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\ge0$
\end_inset

).
 The combined utility of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 can be written as the combined utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{A\in\mathscr{A}}\upsilon(A)w(P(A))$
\end_inset

 - where 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

is the wealth state from the state-space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{A}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A)$
\end_inset

 is the probability of achieving wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)$
\end_inset

 is a probability weighting function for a given probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(A)$
\end_inset

 is the value utility from wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The value function we use is the one used in PT ( Kahneman-Tversky
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KahnemanTversykPT1979"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Rabin 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RabinEU2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and is defined as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\upsilon(\Delta) & =\begin{cases}
\Delta^{\gamma} & \Delta\ge0\\
-\lambda(-\Delta)^{\gamma} & \Delta<0
\end{cases}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just the way the consumer optimises 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u(A))$
\end_inset

 (or equivalently 
\begin_inset Formula $E(A)$
\end_inset

) in the CRRA case for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

, the consumer would optimise 
\begin_inset Formula $u(A\in\mathscr{A})$
\end_inset

 under probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(A_{T}=A)$
\end_inset

 where a certain unobserved factors may contribute to the parameters of
 the probability weighting function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(P(A_{T}=A))$
\end_inset

.
 Keeping the Bernoulli setting with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 at every trial (period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

), the utility to be maximised is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u(A|\psi,p) & =\sum_{A\in\mathscr{A})}\nu(A)w(P(A_{T}=A))
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Other than the non-linear effect of probability, wherein a risk-averse individua
l could see the same opportunity differently from a risk-seeking individual
 (a risk-neutral individual would simply observer 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)=p$
\end_inset

), the above approach also has another property which is of a descriptive
 importance.
 It is that the utility also represents the loss-aversion in wealth (i.e.
 the consumer dislikes losses more than she likes profits).
 See graphs of the probability weighting function for varied degrees of
 risk-aversion 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

