\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 from the non-stochastic approach (
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is a vector of relevant personal characteristics) as an investment towards
 the higher probability of a windfall.
 In other words, if success were a lottery, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 would be the cost to be paid to take part in the lottery.
 This cost may rise steeply as the rich gets richer.
 In the stochastic model, the cost of participation is part of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 which is paid to improve the likelihood of change in wealth.
 So the individual receives the higher likelihood of wealth change only
 after an upfront asset bearing cost 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 is paid.
 Thus the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t,}\rho)$
\end_inset

 in non-stochastic model is included in the structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)$
\end_inset

 in the stochastic model.
 Whether a risk-seeking consumer pays more wealth-bearing costs (or less)
 than a risk-averse - would depend on the overall effect of wealth as well
 as the social stratum.
