\begin_layout Standard
While the Bernoulli trials provide us a general framework for elucidation
 of a PT-based risk-sharing equilibrium, a continuous model could allow
 us to understand the depreciation and interest-related growth using the
 asymptotic properties of continuous distributions.
 As in the discrete case, when there are two players, the two may have the
 same wealth 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},A_{2}$
\end_inset

 but a different appetite for risk.
 The need for the income arrangement may still be needed to prevent an infinite
 gap between 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}>>A_{1}$
\end_inset

we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
dA_{1}=\tau(A_{2}-A_{1})dt-\delta\psi_{1}dt+\sigma(\psi_{1})dW_{1}\\
dA_{2}=-\tau(A_{2}-A_{1})dt-\delta\psi_{2}dt+\sigma(\psi_{2})dW_{2}
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

, the solution to the arithmetic Brownian motion has clear drift and random
 components.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}$
\end_inset

 as constants we can write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
A_{1}=-\psi_{1}t+\sigma(\psi_{1})W_{1}+c_{1}\nonumber \\
A_{2}=-\psi_{2}t+\sigma(\psi_{2})W_{2}+c_{2}\label{eq:arithmetic_brownian}
\end{gather}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the discrete case, we have the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{ij}\equiv P(\Delta A_{ij})=P(A_{i}\rightarrow A_{j})$
\end_inset

 observed by the consumer.
 Every transition 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{ij}=A_{i}-A_{j}$
\end_inset

 consists of a time component and a random component.
 Assuming that a consumer is only looking to optimise the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0T}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 at a time horizon 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, we may use the normal distribution of brownian motion 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{T}$
\end_inset

(i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{T}-W_{0}$
\end_inset

 being normally distributed with variance 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

) to write probability distribution function as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
p(W_{T}=x) & =\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi T}}e^{-\frac{x^{2}}{2T}}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\because\Delta=A_{t}-A_{0}=-\psi t+\sigma(\psi)W_{t}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow W_{t}=\frac{\Delta+\psi t}{\sigma(\psi)}$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

 and a continuous probability weighting function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)$
\end_inset

, a consumer would select 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (and therefore the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $p,\Delta$
\end_inset

 - which would correspond to a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

) such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(p,\Delta)=\int_{p,\Delta}w(p)\nu(\Delta)dpd\Delta$
\end_inset

 is maximised.
 The value function is as defined before i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\upsilon(\Delta) & =\begin{cases}
\Delta^{\gamma} & \Delta\ge0\\
-\lambda(-\Delta)^{\gamma} & \Delta<0
\end{cases}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 The probability weighting function can take forms other than the Karmakar
 function we have used.
 Other options are a prelec function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)=e^{-\beta(-ln\ p)^{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0,\beta>0$
\end_inset

), the Tversky-Kahneman function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)=\frac{p^{\tau}}{(p^{\tau}+(1-p)^{\tau})^{\frac{1}{\tau}}}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in(.279,1)$
\end_inset

 ) or the Goldstein-Einhorn function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)=\frac{\delta p^{\eta}}{\delta p^{\eta}+(1-p)^{\eta}}$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\ge0,\delta\ge0$
\end_inset

).
 The utility which the consumer would minimise is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $E(u)$
\end_inset

 over all possible 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
E(u(\Delta)) & =\int_{\Delta}w(p_{T}(\Delta))\nu(\Delta)d\Delta
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

