 would be if a normal distribution of wealth changes were assumed.
 In the real-world, the choice of the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 may depend very much on the nature of economy.
 As such, the inheritable wealth would decline in value when it's not invested
 in any growing economy.
 In a declining economy (consider depletion of gold in our example), even
 though wealth may depreciate slower it would still keep the consumer's
 relative advantage to others and the consumers would continue to form an
 expectation of increased future wealth just the same.
 It can be argued that wealth in the economy is important not only because
 of the purchasing power but fundamentally due to the social order in the
 form of an expectation held by other participants in the economy that they
 can replicate the success of the wealthy by acting as participants in the
 economy 
