status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the presence of social stratification, such expectations would be segmented
 across social groups.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The nature of the distribution would thus be independent of the state of
 the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We believe that the selection of a distribution is best left for the empirical
 data to dictate - particularly since the choice of risk is hardly one-dimension
al in any real-life scenario.
 At any point, a consumer takes multiple risks by distributing her consumption
 across multiple commodities.
 In a developing economy, basic education may be a high-risk / high-reward
 expenditure if it is sparingly available, but it may be fairly low-risk
 low-reward expenditure in a developed country with state-supported education.
 The expected upside risks with selection of residential neighborhood may
 similarly be fairly low-risk low-reward in densely populated areas but
 low-risk high-reward in rural areas.
 The task to represent all risks the consumers takes in a given economy
 as a one-dimensional random variable is one that may require critical assumptio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key feature of the model is that it allows us to compare status consumption
 in a developed economy with that in a developing economy.
 From the point of view of the consumer's perception of risk - which the
 model incorporates - the most relevant difference between the developing
 countries and the developed countries is that of the strength of welfare
 institutions.
 In a developed economy, the state institutions intervene when market forces
 aren't directed enough to handle financially risky undertakings or to distribut
e items that are identified as public goods.
 On the other hand, the state institutions are generally weaker in the developin
g world - often failing to provide incentives to the private enterprise
 for distribution of public goods.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the determinants of status are public goods, the expectation for their
 growth is less risky than when these are not provided as a public good.
 This has implications for status consumption.
 Consider basic education - which may be of status importance in the developing
 economy in a way that it isn't in the developed economy.
 This is primarily because the distribution of education (and other similar
 assets that may be public goods) is state-assisted in a developed country
 and the expected risk in levels of education of the progeny is lowered.
 Thus, the extent to which education may eventually matter towards status
 in the developed economy depends on how consumers set themselves apart
 in the social order based on other means of signaling status e.g.
 consumption or social identity (since education may no longer differentiate
 them in the social order).
 On the other hand, when a minimum degree of education isn't guaranteed
 by the state (as is the case in a developing economy), the expected growth
 from education is higher (observed probability).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relating inter-generational mobility with status consumption allows us to
 endogenise the role of social characteristics in the population as well.
 In the presence of social segregation or extreme wealth differences, the
 formulation can help answer whether the visible consumption identified
 through surveys can sufficiently capture the concern for status consumption
 or not.
 The uncertainty-based framework can also be used to understand the net
 impact of taxation on the  indirect risk-sharing - which is implied with
 the presence of long-term wealth-differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A possible criticism of the approach may be our assumption that the basic
